Sarina Paris (born December 22, 1973) is a Canadian singer, best known for her international dance-club hits "Look at Us" (2000) and "Just About Enough" (2001).
Born on December 22, 1973, Paris is of Italian descent and grew up in Toronto in a working-class family who were originally from Italy.
She moved back to Italy in 1996 after her mother died to get in touch with her ancestral roots.
In 1995, Paris' debut song "Mystery Man" was released in Canada.

In 1996 during Italian singing contests, she was discovered by Italian manager/producer Vince Tempera (Kill Bill) who invited her to work alongside some of the most respected and talented producers and musicians from La Scala Milano.

A year later she moved to Milan where she worked as a receptionist at a CX music publishing and production where she was discovered by Charlie Marchino and Nico Spinosa of EMI's Italian division, and began her career as an international recording artist.

Sarina returned to the US, continuing to perform in nightclubs but had this desire to sing for her community and so she joined local musicians singing jazz at conferences, local bars and restaurants, and weddings.
Her initial single, "Look at Us", charted on the Billboard Hot 100 in 2001, but did not reach the Top 40.
In 2001, she released her debut album, Sarina Paris, composed of songs she co-wrote, with the exception of a cover version of Cyndi Lauper's "True Colors".
In 2000 "Do You Love Somebody" was released exclusively on the compilation Dancemania x7 in Japan under Toshiba/EMI record label.
Paris toured with La Toya Jackson in Hawaii in May 2004.
For the rest of the 2000s, her music career had been mostly on hold, although she released a new song, "You Are My Valentine", available only on EuroBeats Vol. 3.
Currently ===
On May 27, 2011, nearly marking the tenth anniversary of "Look at Us", Paris released the single "Sophisticated".
Paris would release three new singles in 2019, "Angel Inside", "Believe in Love" and "Where Are You Now".
